definitions: become firm and solid like jelly or gel when cooling or setting
come together to form a clear and definite shape or understanding
examples: The dessert needs two hours to jell in the refrigerator
Add more gelatin if the mixture doesn't jell properly
The team's strategy finally jelled after months of planning
Their ideas began to jell into a workable business plan

definitions: transform into a soft elastic substance like jelly through cooling or chemical process
examples: The fruit mixture will jelly when you add pectin and sugar
Let the broth cool until it starts to jelly naturally

definitions: put something or someone in danger of being harmed lost or destroyed
examples: Don't jeopardize your health by skipping important medical checkups
His reckless behavior could jeopardize the entire project's success

definitions: pull push or twist something with a sudden sharp movement
move with quick sharp motions that are not smooth or controlled
examples: She jerked her hand away from the hot stove immediately
The fisherman jerked the rod upward to set the hook
The old car jerked forward when he pressed the gas pedal
His body jerked involuntarily during the scary movie scene

definitions: speak or act in a playful joking manner without serious intent
examples: He often jests about his cooking skills to make others laugh
The friends jested with each other during their lunch break

definitions: throw goods overboard from a ship or aircraft to make it lighter
get rid of something that is no longer wanted or needed
examples: The pilot had to jettison fuel before making an emergency landing
Ships sometimes jettison cargo during severe storms to stay afloat
The company decided to jettison its unprofitable product lines
We need to jettison old habits that hold us back

definitions: decorate or adorn something with precious stones or jewelry
examples: The craftsman carefully jeweled the crown with diamonds and rubies
She wanted to jewel her wedding dress with small crystals

definitions: dance with quick lively movements especially in folk dancing
move quickly up and down or from side to side with jerky movements
examples: The children jigged happily to the Irish folk music
Everyone started to jig when the fiddle player began
The fishing lure jigs through the water to attract fish
He jigged the key in the lock until it finally opened

definitions: force open a door window or lock using a crowbar or similar tool
examples: The burglar tried to jimmy the back door with a crowbar
They had to jimmy the stuck window to get fresh air

definitions: make or cause to make a light metallic ringing sound
examples: The coins jingle in his pocket as he walks
She jingled her keys to get the baby's attention

definitions: bring bad luck to someone or something by a curse or superstition
examples: Don't talk about winning or you'll jinx our chances
Some players believe wearing certain clothes can jinx their performance

definitions: dance to lively swing or jazz music with energetic movements
talk in a way that is deceptive misleading or meaningless
examples: The couple loved to jive at the local dance hall
Young people would jive to the latest swing bands
Don't jive me with your excuses about being late
He's just jiving when he says he knows famous people

definitions: maneuver or compete for a better position or advantage
ride horses professionally especially in races
examples: The cars jockeyed for position at the start of the race
Politicians jockey for influence within their party
She learned to jockey at a young age on her family's farm
Professional riders jockey thoroughbreds at major racing events

definitions: run at a steady gentle pace especially for physical exercise
give a slight shake push or nudge to something
examples: She jogs three miles every morning before breakfast
Many people jog in the park during their lunch break
Please jog my memory about what happened at the meeting
He jogged her elbow to get her attention

definitions: make someone feel happy cheerful or in good spirits through humor or friendliness
examples: The entertainer tried to jolly the crowd with funny stories
She jollied him along until his bad mood disappeared

definitions: shake or move with a sudden sharp jerky motion
give someone an emotional shock or surprise
examples: The bus jolted to a stop at the traffic light
The earthquake jolted the entire building violently
The unexpected news jolted her out of her complacency
His harsh words jolted me into realizing my mistake

definitions: tease someone in a playful good-natured way without harmful intent
examples: The siblings often josh each other about their different hobbies
Don't take it seriously when he joshes you about your accent

definitions: fight on horseback with lances as medieval knights did
engage in combat or competition especially verbal sparring
examples: Knights would joust in tournaments to display their skills
The actors learned to joust safely for the medieval film
The lawyers jousted verbally during the heated court case
Politicians often joust over policy issues in debates

definitions: take a vehicle and drive it fast and dangerously for excitement often without permission
examples: Teenagers sometimes joyride in stolen cars late at night
He decided to joyride in his father's sports car

definitions: keep several objects in the air by repeatedly throwing and catching them
manage or deal with several tasks activities or responsibilities at once
examples: The circus performer can juggle five balls at once
She learned to juggle oranges during her summer vacation
Working parents often juggle career demands with family responsibilities
He struggles to juggle his studies and part-time job

definitions: mix things up in a confused disorderly way without any organization
examples: Don't jumble all the papers together in one drawer
The moving truck jumbled our carefully packed boxes

definitions: start a vehicle engine using electrical cables connected to another battery
give something a quick energetic start to get it going
examples: Can you help me jumpstart my car with your cables
I keep jumper cables to jumpstart dead batteries
The new funding will jumpstart our research project immediately
Morning coffee helps jumpstart my brain for work

definitions: travel in or paddle a small narrow boat originally used by Inuit peoples
examples: We plan to kayak down the river this weekend
She learned to kayak in calm lake waters first

definitions: fall over sideways suddenly often from illness weakness or being off balance
examples: The heat made him keel over during the outdoor ceremony
The old tree finally keeled over in the strong wind

definitions: put a dog or dogs in a kennel for boarding or shelter
examples: We kennel our dogs when we travel for vacation
The breeder kennels her show dogs in heated buildings

definitions: deliver the main speech at a conference or event that sets the central theme
examples: The CEO will keynote the technology conference next month
She was invited to keynote at three major events

definitions: take someone away illegally by force usually to demand money for their release
examples: The criminals planned to kidnap the wealthy businessman's daughter
Pirates sometimes kidnap sailors and demand ransom payments

definitions: start a fire or cause something to start burning
arouse or inspire an emotion interest or feeling in someone
examples: Use dry twigs to kindle the campfire more easily
A single spark can kindle a forest fire
The teacher's enthusiasm kindled a love of science in her students
His speech kindled hope in the hearts of listeners

definitions: form or cause to form a sharp twist or bend in something flexible
examples: The garden hose tends to kink when you coil it
Be careful not to kink the cable while installing

definitions: fly a kite or move through air like a kite
fraudulently write checks without sufficient funds hoping to cover them later
examples: Children love to kite on windy days at the beach
The colorful dragon kites soar high above the park
He was arrested for kiting checks between multiple bank accounts
Some businesses lose money when customers kite checks

definitions: go down on one or both knees especially as a sign of respect worship or submission
examples: People kneel in church during certain parts of the service
The knight had to kneel before the king

definitions: give someone the rank of knight as an honor for achievement or service
examples: The Queen will knight him for his contributions to medicine
Medieval kings would knight brave warriors after battles

definitions: make fabric or garments by interlocking loops of yarn with needles
join or cause to join together closely and firmly
examples: My grandmother taught me to knit warm scarves
She knits sweaters for all her grandchildren
The broken bone will knit back together in six weeks
Shared experiences knit the community members together

definitions: fasten or tie string rope or fabric by making a knot
examples: Remember to knot the rope securely before climbing
The sailor showed us how to knot different types

definitions: apply oneself seriously to a task and work hard at it
examples: You need to knuckle down and study for your exams
After vacation she knuckled down to finish the project

definitions: work hard doing physical work especially for wages
work at something with great effort and difficulty
examples: Farmers labour in the fields from dawn to dusk
Construction workers labour in all types of weather
She laboured over her thesis for months before completion
The old car laboured up the steep mountain road

definitions: fasten or tighten shoes or clothing by threading laces through holes
add alcohol or drugs to food or drink often secretly
examples: Remember to lace your boots tightly before hiking
The corset was difficult to lace without help
Someone laced the punch with rum at the party
He laced his coffee with whiskey on cold mornings

definitions: coat or cover something with lacquer varnish for protection or shine
examples: The craftsman will lacquer the wooden box for durability
She decided to lacquer her nails with clear polish

definitions: develop a run or vertical tear in stockings or tights
examples: Be careful not to ladder your new tights on that rough chair
Her stockings laddered when she caught them on a nail

definitions: load a person vehicle or container heavily with a large amount
examples: The workers laden the truck with boxes of produce
Ships were laden with gold from the New World

definitions: serve or transfer liquid food using a large long-handled spoon
examples: She ladled hot soup into bowls for the guests
The cook ladled gravy over the roasted meat

definitions: fail to keep pace with others or fall behind expected progress
examples: Don't lag behind the group during the mountain hike
Sales continue to lag despite new marketing efforts

definitions: run away quickly especially from law enforcement or to escape trouble
examples: The thieves decided to lam before police arrived
He had to lam out of town after the scandal

definitions: give birth to a lamb as a sheep does during lambing season
examples: The ewes usually lamb in early spring each year
The farmer stays up all night when sheep lamb

definitions: cause a person or animal to be unable to walk properly
examples: The accident lamed the horse and ended its racing career
Poor-fitting shoes can lame a person over time

definitions: express grief sorrow or regret about something deeply and often
examples: The widow continued to lament her husband's death
Critics lament the loss of traditional craftsmanship

definitions: cover paper or other material with transparent plastic for protection
examples: Teachers often laminate educational posters to preserve them
I need to laminate my ID card before it tears

definitions: publicly criticize or ridicule someone or something with harsh satire
examples: The comedy show loves to lampoon politicians and celebrities
The cartoonist lampooned the mayor's new policies

definitions: pierce or wound with a lance or spear weapon
cut open an abscess or boil to drain infected material
examples: Medieval knights would lance their opponents during battle
The warrior lanced the target with perfect accuracy
The doctor needs to lance the boil to relieve pressure
They lanced the abscess to drain the infection

definitions: become invalid or expire through passage of time or lack of renewal
gradually fall or slip into a particular state or condition
examples: Don't let your insurance policy lapse by missing payments
His membership lapsed after he forgot to renew
She tends to lapse into silence when feeling upset
The patient lapsed into unconsciousness after the accident
